The structural transitions in SrIrO$_{3}$ are less certain than for other perovskites. \begin{itemize} \item The ground state is usually believed to be \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_mC60_15_af_e4f_ef-001}{monoclinic with space group $C2/c$ \#15}, however \item (Schmalle, 1990) found a somewhat disordered room temperature \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B6C7_cI90_204_e_dg_ac2f-001}{cubic phase} (this structure). \item (Longo, 1971) found that to the right of a line from (700$^\circ$C, 5\,GPa) to (1650$^\circ$, 2\,GPa) there is a transformation to the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_oP20_62_c_cd_a-001}{orthorhombic CaTiO$_{3}$ structure}, but \item (Wang, 2024) found a \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_tP10_123_g_abi_cd-001}{tetragonal double perovskite structure} formed at 1400$^\circ$C and 6\,GPa, well into the range where (Longo, 1971) found the orthorhombic structure. This structure is very close to \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_cP5_221_a_c_b-001}{cubic perovskite ($E2_{1}$)}, which may well be the structure found at higher pressures and temperatures. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-0.25in} 
 The Greek letters used to designate the phase are arbitrarily assigned in the order of the first publication describing the phases. 
 All of the strontium sites in this structure are sparsely populated.  The occupation numbers from (Schmalle, 1990) do not give the correct stoichiometry, so we use the values from the ICSD entry.  The occupations are: \begin{itemize} \item Sr I 33.6\% \item Sr II 12.0\%  \item Sr III 23.4\% \item Sr IV 30.0\% \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 These values give a stoichiometry of Sr$_{0.848}$IrO$_{3}$.
